  "prompt": "What can cause astigmatism?",
  "response": "Astigmatism is primarily caused by an irregular shape of the cornea or the lens inside the eye. Instead of having a perfectly spherical shape, the cornea or lens may be more oblong, like a football, leading to distorted vision for both near and far objects. Several factors can contribute to the development of astigmatism, including:\n\n1. **Genetics**: Astigmatism often runs in families, suggesting a genetic predisposition.\n2. **Eye injuries**: Trauma or injury to the eye can cause scarring on the cornea, leading to irregularities.\n3. **Surgery**: Certain types of eye surgery, particularly those involving the cornea, may alter its shape and result in astigmatism.\n4. **Keratoconus**: This is a progressive eye disease where the cornea thins and begins to bulge into a cone-like shape, causing astigmatism.\n5. **Other eye conditions**: Conditions such as pterygium, where a benign growth forms on the cornea, can disrupt its normal shape and lead to astigmatism.\n\nRegular eye examinations are important for diagnosing and managing astigmatism effectively. Treatments can include corrective lenses, such as glasses or contact lenses, and in some cases, refractive surgery.",
